To create a FEN notation for a chessboard in Latex, you can use the `fen` command from the `chess` library in the `xparse` package. You need to provide the coordinates of the pieces on the chessboard, as well as the number of columns and rows. Here's a simple example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xparse}
\usepackage{chess}
\begin{document}
\begin{fen}
% Coordinates of the pieces on the chessboard
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 h6 10. d4 Bg4 11. Nbd2 Nd7 12. Ng5 Bh7 13. Qd2 f5 14. Rad1 Qf6
% Number of columns and rows of the chessboard
8/8/8/8/8/8/8/2 KQkq - - 0 1
\end{fen}
\end{document}
```
You need two characters to represent the pieces on the chessboard:
* The first column contains the black pieces, the second column contains the white pieces, and each row contains a piece. The characters used are: `N` for the black queen, `B` for the white queen, `R` for the black king, `Q` for the white king, `K` for the black bishop, `k` for the white bishop, `n` for the black knight, `N` for the white knight, `b` for the black rook, and `B` for the white rook. For example, `Bb3` represents a white rook on the third row of the chessboard.
* The following characters are used to indicate the possible movements of the pieces: `e4`, which represents the movement of a piece one square vertically to the right; `h3`, which represents the movement of a piece one square horizontally to the left; `Qd2`, which represents the movement of a piece one square diagonally to the right; and `f5`, which represents the movement of a piece one square diagonally to the left. Then, you can use parentheses to indicate alternative possible movements of the pieces, as in this case with the movement of the black rook from the eighth row to the seventh or ninth row (indicated by the parentheses). You can use any combination of the above characters to describe any possible movement on the chessboard.

